# Section Composition Standards

## The Repetition Problem

The most common way a website looks "templated" is when every section uses the same structural formula: `eyebrow label → h2 heading → body paragraph → content block`. This pattern is recognizable and generic at 3+ uses per page. It signals template, not craft.

**Rule: The `eyebrow → h2 → paragraph` header pattern is limited to 3 sections per homepage.** Remaining sections must use a different entry point.

## Forbidden Anti-Patterns

### 1. Unbalanced 2-column grid headers
Using `grid grid-cols-2` for a heading-on-left + description-on-right header where content heights are unpredictable. This creates dead whitespace when one column is taller.

**Forbidden:**
```tsx
<div className="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-[1fr_380px] gap-10">
  <div><h2>Heading</h2></div>
  <div><p>Paragraph that might be much longer or shorter than the heading</p></div>
</div>
```

**Use instead:** Full-width heading with the description positioned below-right:
```tsx
<div className="flex flex-col gap-4">
  <h2>Heading</h2>
  <div className="flex justify-end">
    <p className="max-w-sm text-right lg:text-left">Description</p>
  </div>
</div>
```

Or: stacked layout where heading is full-width and description is a single narrower line below it.

### 2. Consecutive sections with the same grid structure
No two consecutive sections may use the same primary layout grid (e.g., two 3-column card grids back to back). Break the rhythm intentionally.

### 3. Background alternation as the only section differentiation
Alternating `bg-white` / `bg-whisper-gray` without any compositional variation between sections creates a striped effect that reads as template. Background differentiation must be paired with layout differentiation.

### 4. All headings at the same size
If every section h2 is `clamp(38px, 4.5vw, 60px)`, the page has no typographic hierarchy at a macro level. At least one section should break the size rhythm — either significantly larger or significantly smaller and paired with something else carrying the visual weight.

### 5. Standard card grids without variation
A grid of 4–6 identical cards with the same padding, border-radius, and content structure repeated across multiple sections. Cards must vary — mix open list rows with contained cards, or vary card sizes within a grid.

---

## Required Compositional Variety

Every homepage must contain at least **2 Compositional Moments** — sections where the layout departs significantly from a standard grid. Classify each section before building:

| Level | Description | Examples |
|---|---|---|
| **Standard** | Clean content section, standard grid, standard heading | Services card grid, Insurance panel |
| **Elevated** | Section has a distinct structural choice that differs from its neighbors | Full-width heading with right-positioned sub, numbered editorial list |
| **Signature** | The layout itself is the visual; the section makes you stop | Mega heading at 100px+, giant pull-quote filling a dark section, conditions as flowing magazine typography |

At least 2 sections must be **Signature** level.

---

## Section Composition Plan (required before building)

Before writing any section's code, define its treatment in one line:

```
Section: [Name]
Level: Standard / Elevated / Signature
Layout: [e.g. "mega-heading full-width, conditions in 2-col editorial list below"]
Heading pattern: [e.g. "none — quote IS the heading" / "full-width h2 only, no eyebrow" / "standard eyebrow+h2"]
Background: [token name]
Compositional departure: [what makes this not a generic grid, or "none" for Standard]
```

If a section is Standard, make sure it's not consecutive with another Standard section.

---

## Grid Alignment Rules

When a 2-column split IS used and content height imbalance is possible:

- Use `items-end` when the right column (description) tends to be longer than the left (heading)
- Use `items-start` when the left column (heading) tends to be taller
- Never rely on a column layout being visually balanced when content is dynamic or prose-length

---

## Typography Contrast at Page Scale

Squint at the page. Every heading should be roughly the same visual weight — if they are, the page looks flat. At least one section should have a heading at 2× or more the standard h2 size (i.e., 100px+ on desktop), and at least one section should have no display heading at all — letting the content itself carry the section.
